introduction.p:
The point of forms is not to make old problems look fancier. The point is to make the
shape of the theorem visible:
\boxed{\int_{\partial M}\omega=\int_M d\omega.}

subsection.p:
For work or circulation, we use a 1-form:
\boxed{\omega=P\,dx+Q\,dy}
in the plane, or
\boxed{\omega=P\,dx+Q\,dy+R\,dz}
in space.

Let C be the unit circle, oriented counterclockwise: x=\cos t,\qquad y=\sin t,\qquad 0\le t\le2\pi. Then dx=-\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=\cos t\,dt. Pull back the form:
\omega \amp = -\sin t(-\sin t\,dt)+\cos t(\cos t\,dt) \amp = (\sin^2t+\cos^2t)\,dt \amp = dt.
Therefore \boxed{\oint_C\omega=\int_0^{2\pi}dt=2\pi.}

