subsection.p:
      Your task.
      Study one closed form on a punctured domain. Use one of the following.

\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{Form} \amp \text{Domain} \\ \hline
\displaystyle
\omega_1=\frac{-y\,dx+x\,dy}{x^2+y^2}
\amp
\mathbb R^2\setminus\{(0,0)\}
\\[4mm]
\displaystyle
\omega_2=\frac{x\,dx+y\,dy}{x^2+y^2}
\amp
\mathbb R^2\setminus\{(0,0)\}
\\[4mm]
\displaystyle
\omega_3=
\frac{-(y-b)\,dx+(x-a)\,dy}{(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2}
\amp
\mathbb R^2\setminus\{(a,b)\}
\end{array}

First compute the exterior derivative:
d\Phi \amp = d(x\,dy\wedge dz) + d(y\,dz\wedge dx) + d(z\,dx\wedge dy) \amp = dx\wedge dy\wedge dz + dy\wedge dz\wedge dx + dz\wedge dx\wedge dy.
Both dy\wedge dz\wedge dx and dz\wedge dx\wedge dy are cyclic rearrangements of dx\wedge dy\wedge dz, so they have the same sign. Thus \boxed{d\Phi=3\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.} Therefore \boxed{\int_B d\Phi=3.}

Thus
\boxed{\int_{\partial B}\Phi=1+1+1=3.}
So
\boxed{\int_{\partial B}\Phi=\int_B d\Phi.}

Your task. Verify the generalized Stokes theorem on a rectangular box or cube. Choose one of these.
\begin{array}{c|c} \text{Region} \amp \text{Form} \\ \hline [0,1]^3 \amp x\,dy\wedge dz+y\,dz\wedge dx+z\,dx\wedge dy\\[1mm] [0,a]\times[0,b]\times[0,c] \amp x^2\,dy\wedge dz+y\,dz\wedge dx+z\,dx\wedge dy\\[1mm] [0,1]^2 \amp (x^2+y)\,dx+xy\,dy\\[1mm] [0,a]\times[0,b] \amp -y\,dx+x\,dy \end{array}
The three-dimensional choices verify the divergence theorem in forms language. The two-dimensional choices verify Green's theorem in forms language.

A seed example: the annulus and the inner boundary. Let A be the annulus 1\le x^2+y^2\le4. Consider the 1-form \boxed{\eta=\frac12(x\,dy-y\,dx).} Then
d\eta \amp = \frac12(dx\wedge dy-dy\wedge dx) \amp = dx\wedge dy.
So Green's theorem says \boxed{\int_{\partial A}\eta = \int_A dx\wedge dy = \operatorname{Area}(A).}

